==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lush
<hw>Lush</hw> <pr>(l⟦ucr⟧sh)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Prob. an abbrev.
of <ets>lushious</ets>, fr. <ets>luscious</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Full of juice or succulence.</def> <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How <qex>lush</qex> and lusty the grass looks! how green!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having thick and luxurient vegetation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Characterized by abundance or luxurience;
rich.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lush</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lush
<hw>Lush</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymol uncertain; said
to be fr. <etsep>Lushington</etsep>, name of a London brewer.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Liquor, esp. intoxicating liquor; drink.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark> <rj><au>C. Lever.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>an habitual drunkard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lushburg</ent>⟦br⟧
